<section>
  <h2>Overview</h2>

  <div class="narrative">
    <p>The Citadel of Knowledge rises atop Mount Chronique, its pale stone towers piercing the clouds like so many fingers reaching for the stars. Built centuries ago by the first Archivists, this titanic fortress is the beating heart of all the kingdom's knowledge. Its walls, carved from limestone quarried in the forgotten pits of Valmarbre, have taken on a silver tint over the ages that gleams under the moon and shimmers in the sun.</p>
    <p>The wind whistles perpetually between its towers, carrying with it the murmurs of thousands of parchments. Travelers who catch their first glimpse of it from the valley stand speechless before the sheer immensity of the edifice - seven main towers linked by suspended walkways, hundreds of narrow windows from which a golden light filters at all hours, and a central dome covered in patinated copper that houses the Grand Archive.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="fancy-separator"></div>

<section>
  <h2>Architecture and main halls</h2>

  <div class="narrative">
    <p>The interior of the Citadel is a labyrinth of corridors, spiral staircases, and vaulted chambers. Miles of shelving line the walls, sagging under the weight of parchment scrolls, leather-bound codices, and engraved stone tablets. The air is thick with the heady scent of ancient ink and aged paper. Enchanted lanterns float gently along the ceilings, casting a warm and steady light that never tires the eyes of the scribes.</p>
    <p>On the ground floor lie the <strong>Three Halls of Knowledge</strong> - the very heart of the Guild's archiving system. Higher up are the Archivists' quarters, the copying workshops, the Oracle's Chamber, and the ink laboratories. Below ground, accessible only through a secret staircase, stretch the crypts where the oldest archives rest and the Time Weaver's Workshop, where reality itself seems to bend.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="fancy-separator"></div>

<section>
  <h2>History</h2>

  <div class="narrative">
    <p>The Citadel was erected in the aftermath of the Great Erasure, that catastrophe which saw the entire chronicles of the Kingdom of Versalia vanish in a single night. Nobody knows exactly what happened - some speak of a magical fire, others of a destruction spell cast by a jealous enemy. What is certain is that centuries of history were reduced to nothing. Never again, the survivors swore. Never again.</p>
    <p>The first Archivists - a handful of scribes, scholars, and mages - took forty years to build the Citadel. They wove into it magical protections against fire, water, theft, and even time itself. Every stone was laid with a preservation enchantment. It is said that even if the entire world crumbled, the Citadel would still stand, a silent guardian of the peoples' memory.</p>
    <p>Today, the Citadel welcomes hundreds of Archivists and dozens of recruits each season. It is a living place, bustling with activity, where past and present dwell side by side in studious harmony.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="fancy-separator"></div>

<section>
  <h2>Access and surroundings</h2>

  <div class="narrative">
    <p>The Citadel is reached via the Chroniclers' Road, a paved path that winds from the lower town of Versalia through Darkwood Forest. The journey takes half a day on foot, but recruits often make it at a run, eager to discover their new life. Two monumental iron-banded oak doors guard the main entrance, flanked by statues depicting the Guild's founders.</p>
    <p>From the highest towers, on a clear day, one can glimpse in the distance the Valley of Eternal Forges, whose blue flames light up the horizon at night. To the east, the Distant Portals shimmer faintly - those magical arches that connect the Citadel to the far-off archives of other guilds across the continent.</p>
  </div>
</section>
